        "A parking garage at 15 years old shows widespread cracking, delamination, and rust staining on the suspended slabs. What is the diagnosis and recommended approach?",
        "This is a textbook presentation of chloride-induced reinforcement corrosion in a parking structure exposed to de-icing salts. The sequence: de-icing chemicals tracked in by vehicles dissolve chlorides that penetrate the concrete cover through surface cracks. At the reinforcement level, chlorides destroy the passive oxide layer protecting the steel, initiating corrosion. Corrosion products expand, cracking the concrete parallel to the rebars and eventually causing delamination (horizontal fracture planes at the rebar level). Rust staining is oxidation products migrating to the surface. At 15 years with this level of distress, the structure likely has widespread chloride contamination beyond the currently visible damage. Recommended approach: (1) Conduct a full condition survey: visual, delamination (chain drag/hammer), half-cell potential mapping, chloride profiling at representative locations, and core testing. (2) Develop a repair strategy: remove delaminated concrete, clean rebar, apply corrosion inhibitor, patch with low-permeability repair mortar, and install a traffic-bearing waterproofing membrane. (3) Consider cathodic protection for areas with high chloride but no visible damage yet. (4) Implement a maintenance program with annual sealer application."
