        "A precast concrete wall panel has a diagonal crack running from corner to corner. It appeared during stripping from the form. What happened?",
        "A corner-to-corner diagonal crack in a precast panel during stripping (demolding) is almost certainly caused by improper lifting or an incorrect lifting configuration. When a panel is stripped from a horizontal form, the lifting points, panel self-weight, and suction from the form create a complex stress state. If the lifting points are not properly positioned, or if one lift point engages before the others, the panel can experience bending and torsion far exceeding the design assumptions. A diagonal corner-to-corner crack indicates torsional stress: the panel twisted because it was supported on three corners while the fourth hung free, or because suction release was not uniform. Other possible causes: inadequate panel strength at the time of stripping (concrete had not reached the minimum required stripping strength, typically 15-20 MPa), form deformation causing restraint, or embedded items creating stress concentrations. The panel is likely rejected for structural use. Prevention: follow the lifting plan exactly, verify concrete strength before stripping with maturity testing or cylinder breaks, apply form release agent consistently, and break suction gradually before lifting."
