        "How do cracks in post-tensioned concrete differ from those in conventionally reinforced concrete?",
        "Post-tensioned (PT) concrete is designed to remain uncracked under service loads because the prestressing force puts the entire section in compression. Therefore, any visible crack in a PT member is potentially more significant than in reinforced concrete where cracking is expected. Key differences: (1) Cracking in PT members indicates the section has decompressed and the applied moment exceeds the cracking moment, which may mean the prestress force has been lost (tendon corrosion, anchorage failure, or relaxation beyond design assumptions). (2) Cracks in PT members expose tendons to corrosion, which is especially critical for unbonded tendons where corrosion is not confined to a single section. (3) Longitudinal cracks parallel to tendons may indicate grout voids in bonded PT systems, tendon corrosion and expansion, or bursting stresses at anchorage zones. (4) Cracks at anchorage zones (spalling, splitting) suggest inadequate confinement reinforcement or overloading. Any cracking in PT structures warrants investigation of the tendon condition: void mapping with GPR or impact-echo, invasive inspection at selected locations, and force verification with lift-off tests at anchorages."
