        "I'm inspecting a 30-year-old concrete bridge. I found diagonal cracks near the supports of the main girders. The cracks are approximately 0.4 mm wide at the web and extend from near the bottom flange toward the top flange at about 40 degrees.",
        "These are shear cracks, and at 0.4 mm width in a 30-year-old bridge girder, this is a significant finding. The 40-degree angle, location near supports (high shear zone), and propagation from the bottom toward the compression flange are all characteristic of shear distress. This is more critical than flexural cracking because shear failure in concrete can be sudden and brittle. Immediate actions: install crack monitors on the widest cracks to check for progressive growth, assess if the bridge needs load restrictions or emergency shoring, and commission a detailed structural capacity assessment. Do not wait to act on this.",
