        "How do I assess crack severity in concrete pavements using the Pavement Condition Index (PCI) method?",
        "The PCI method (ASTM D6433) rates pavement distresses by type, severity, and extent. For concrete pavements, crack-related distresses include: Linear cracking (longitudinal, transverse, diagonal): Low severity is sealed or unsealed cracks with no spalling or faulting. Medium severity is moderate spalling less than 75 mm or faulting less than 15 mm. High severity is severe spalling, faulting greater than 15 mm, or cracks greater than 75 mm wide. Corner breaks: Low (no spalling or faulting), medium (spalling or faulting less than 15 mm), high (significant spalling or faulting). Durability (D) cracking: Low (cracks with no loose material), medium (some loose material), high (extensive loose material and punchout potential). Each distress type has a deduct value curve that reduces the PCI score from 100 (perfect). The PCI number drives maintenance decisions: 85-100 is good (preventive maintenance), 70-85 fair (minor rehab), 55-70 poor (major rehab), below 55 is very poor (reconstruction). Detailed survey procedures involve walking each sample unit, identifying and measuring each distress, and calculating the weighted PCI."
