        "Explain how construction overloading leads to early-age cracking.",
        "Early-age construction overloading is a common but often overlooked cause of cracking in concrete structures. The issue occurs when construction loads (equipment, material stockpiling, formwork from upper floors, or shoring loads) are applied to recently placed concrete before it has developed adequate strength. Young concrete (1-7 days) may have only 20-50% of its design 28-day strength, yet construction schedules often demand that new slabs support significant loads soon after placement. The result is flexural cracking in slabs (often near columns or supports), shear cracking in beams receiving early construction loads, and punching shear distress in flat plates loaded by reshoring from upper floor formwork. Prevention requires a formwork and reshoring analysis that accounts for actual concrete strength gain (monitored by maturity method or early-age cylinder breaks), limits on construction live loads at each stage, and awareness that reshoring from multiple floors above can impose loads on lower floors exceeding the design service load."
