    # ===== ADDITIONAL INSPECTION =====
    msg(
        "How is infrared thermography used in crack and delamination detection?",
        "Infrared (IR) thermography detects subsurface delaminations and voids by imaging surface temperature differences caused by variations in thermal conductivity. Intact concrete conducts heat relatively uniformly, but a delamination (horizontal fracture plane, often at the rebar level from corrosion) traps air, which is a thermal insulator. When the concrete surface is heated (by solar radiation, typically) or cooled (at night), the surface above a delamination warms or cools faster than sound areas, creating a temperature contrast visible on the IR camera. For crack detection specifically, IR can identify active water flow through cracks (cooler linear features from evaporative cooling) and map the extent of delamination zones that often accompany surface cracking. Best results are obtained during rapid temperature transitions: early morning solar warming or late afternoon cooling, with at least a 10C difference between slab surface and air temperature. Limitations: wind, rain, shading, and surface treatments can mask or mimic defects."
    ),
